# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: certification
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:certification/abbreviations-com] As of 2016 the website includes nearly a million definitions that are classified by a large variety of categories from computing and the Web to governmental, military, medicine and more.
[src:certification/abbreviations-com] The database is being built by contributing editors, who can sign up on the website and help expanding it by submitting new entries for inclusion.
[src:certification/abbreviations-com] The website also offers its content to be freely used by third-parties through its open APIs.
[src:certification/abbreviations-com] In 2005 the website has been selected as one of the "101 Best Web Sites for Writers" by the American magazine Writer's Digest.
[src:certification/abbreviations-com] In 2010 the Abbreviations.com website has been selected as one of the "Best Free Reference Web Sites" by the ALA's Reference and User Services Association.
[src:certification/abbreviations-com] In 2015 the website's parent company STANDS4 has won the Red Herring Top 100 Europe award.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] An **academic degree** is a qualification awarded to a student upon successful completion of a course of study in higher education.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] Academic degrees are commonly structured in levels, most often categorized as undergraduate and postgraduate degrees.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] The most common undergraduate qualification is the bachelor's degree, although some educational systems also offer lower-level degrees such as the associate degree or the foundation degree.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] Postgraduate degrees include the engineer's degree, the master's degree, and the doctorate.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] In the UK and countries whose educational systems are based on the British system, honours degrees are divided into classes: first, second (broken into upper second, or 2.1, and lower second, or 2.2) and third class.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] The doctorate (Latin: *doceo*, "I teach") first appeared in medieval Europe as a license to teach (Latin: *licentia docendi*) at a medieval university.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] Its roots can be traced to the early church when the term "doctor" referred to the Apostles, Church Fathers and other Christian authorities who taught and interpreted the Bible.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] The right to grant a *licentia docendi* was originally reserved by the church which required the applicant to pass a test, take an oath of allegiance, and pay a fee.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] The Third Council of the Lateran of 1179 guaranteed the access – now largely free of charge – of all able applicants, who were, however, still tested for aptitude by the ecclesiastic scholastic.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] This right remained a point of contention between the church authorities and the slowly emancipating universities, but was granted by the Pope to the University of Paris in 1231 where it became a universal license to teach (*licentia ubique docendi*).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] While the *licentia* continued to hold a higher prestige than the bachelor's degree (*Baccalaureus*), it was ultimately reduced to an intermediate step to the Magister and doctorate, both of which now became the exclusive qualification for teaching.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] In universities, doctoral training was a form of apprenticeship to a guild.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] The traditional term of study before new teachers were admitted to the guild of "Master of Arts" was seven years.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] This was the same as the term of apprenticeship for other occupations.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] Originally the terms "master" and "doctor" were synonymous, but over time the doctorate came to be regarded as a higher qualification than the master's degree.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] Today the terms "master" (from the Latin *magister*, lit.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] 'teacher'), "Doctor", and "Professor" signify different levels of academic achievement, but in the Medieval university, they were equivalent terms.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] The use of them in the degree name was a matter of custom at a university.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] Most universities conferred the Master of Arts, although the highest degree was often termed Master of Theology/Divinity or Doctor of Theology/Divinity, depending on the place.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] The earliest doctoral degrees (theology – *Divinitatis* Doctor (D.D.), law – *Legum* Doctor (LL.D., later D.C.L.) and medicine – *Medicinæ* Doctor (M.D., D.M.)) reflected the historical separation of all higher university study into these three fields.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] Over time, the D.D. has gradually become less common outside theology and is now mostly used for honorary degrees, with the title "Doctor of Theology" being used more often for earned degrees.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] Studies outside theology, law, and medicine were then called "philosophy", due to the Renaissance conviction that real knowledge could be derived from empirical observation.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] The degree title of Doctor of Philosophy is a much later creation and was not introduced in England before 1900.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] Studies in what once was called philosophy are now classified as sciences and humanities.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] George Makdisi theorizes that the *ijazah* issued in medieval Islamic madrasas in the 9th century was the origin of the doctorate that later appeared in medieval European universities.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] Alfred Guillaume, Syed Farid al-Attas and Devin J.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] Stewart agree that there is a resemblance between the *ijazah* and the university degree.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] However, Toby Huff and others reject Makdisi's theory.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] Stewart finds that the *ijazat al-ifta*, license to teach Islamic law and issue legal opinions, is most similar to the medieval European university degree in that it permits entry into certain professions.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] A key difference was that the granting authority of the *ijaza* was an individual professor whereas the university degree was granted by a corporate entity.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] The University of Bologna in Italy, regarded as the oldest university in Europe, was the first institution to confer the degree of Doctor in Civil Law in the late 12th century; it also conferred similar degrees in other subjects, including medicine.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] The University of Paris used the term "master" for its graduates, a practice adopted by the English universities of Oxford and Cambridge, as well as the ancient Scottish universities of St Andrews, Glasgow, Aberdeen and Edinburgh.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] The term "bachelor" comes from the Latin *baccalaureus*, a term previously used to describe a squire (i.e., apprentice) to a knight.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] Further study and, in particular, successful participation in, and moderation of, disputations would earn one the Master of Arts degree, from the Latin magister, "master" (typically indicating a teacher), entitling one to teach these subjects.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] Masters of Arts were eligible to enter study under the "higher faculties" of Law, Medicine or Theology and earn first a bachelor's and then master's or doctor's degree in these subjects.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] Thus, a degree was only a step on the way to becoming a fully qualified master – hence the English word "graduate", which is based on the Latin *gradus* ("step").
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] The naming of degrees eventually became linked to the subjects studied.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] Scholars in the faculties of arts or grammar became known as "masters", but those in theology, medicine and law were known as "doctors".
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] As a study in the arts or grammar was a necessary prerequisite to study in subjects such as theology, medicine and law, the degree of doctor assumed a higher status than the master's degree.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] This led to the modern hierarchy in which the Doctor of Philosophy (Ph.D.), which in its present form as a degree based on research and dissertation is a development from 18th- and 19th-century German universities, is a more advanced degree than the Master of Arts (M.A.).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] The practice of using the term *doctor* for PhDs developed within German universities and spread across the academic world.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] The French terminology is tied closely to the original meanings of the terms.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] "bachelor") is conferred upon French students who have completed their secondary education and allows the student to attend university.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] When students graduate from university, they are awarded a *licence*, much as the medieval teaching guilds would have done, and they are qualified to teach in secondary schools or proceed to higher-level studies.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] Spain had a similar structure: the term *"Bachiller"* was used for those who finished the secondary or high-school level education, known as *"Bachillerato"*.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] The standard Spanish university 5-year degree was *"Licenciado"*, (although there were a few 3-year associate degrees called *"diplomaturas"*, from where the *"diplomados"* could move to study a related *licenciatura*).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] In the past, degrees have been directly issued by the authority of the monarch or by a bishop, rather than any educational institution.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] In Great Britain, Lambeth degrees are still awarded by the Archbishop of Canterbury.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] The Archbishop of Canterbury's right to grant degrees is derived from the Peter's Pence Act 1533, which empowered the Archbishop to grant dispensations previously granted by the Pope.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] Among educational institutions, St David's College, Lampeter, was granted limited degree awarding powers by royal charter in the nineteenth century, despite not being a university.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] The University College of North Staffordshire was also granted degree awarding powers on its foundation in 1949, despite not becoming a university (as the University of Keele) until 1962.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] Following the Education Reform Act 1988, many educational institutions other than universities have been granted degree-awarding powers, including higher education colleges and colleges of the University of London, many of which are now effectively universities in their own right.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] In many countries, gaining an academic degree entitles the holder to assume distinctive academic dress particular to the awarding institution, identifying the status of the individual wearing them.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] In many countries, degrees may only be awarded by institutions authorised to do so by the national or regional government.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] Frequently, governments will also regulate the use of the word *university* in the names of businesses.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] This approach is followed, for example, by Australia, the United Kingdom and Israel.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] The use of fake degrees by individuals, either obtained from a bogus institution or simply invented, is often covered by fraud laws.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] Depending on the culture and the degree earned, degrees may be indicated by a pre-nominal title, post-nominal letters, a choice of either, or not indicated at all.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] In countries influenced by the UK, post-nominal letters are the norm, with only doctorates granting a title, while titles are the norm in many northern European countries.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] Depending on the culture and the purpose of the listing, only the highest degree, a selection of degrees, or all degrees might be listed.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] The awarding institution may be shown and it might be specified if a degree was at honours level, particularly where the honours degree is a separate qualification from the ordinary bachelor's degree.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] For member institutions of the Association of Commonwealth Universities, there is a standard list of abbreviations for university names given in the Commonwealth Universities Yearbook.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] In practice, many variations are used and the Yearbook notes that the abbreviations used may not match those used by the universities concerned.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] Other Latin abbreviations commonly used include 'Cantuar' for Lambeth degrees (awarded by the Archbishop of Canterbury), 'Dunelm' for Durham University, 'Ebor' for the University of York and 'Exon' for the University of Exeter.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] The Ancient universities of Scotland and the University of London have abbreviations that are the same in English and Latin.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] Confusion can result from universities sharing similar names, e.g. the University of York in the UK and York University in Canada or Newcastle University in the UK and the University of Newcastle in Australia.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] In this case, the convention is to include a country abbreviation with the university's name.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] For example, 'York (Can.)' and 'York (UK)' or 'Newc (UK)' and 'Newc (Aus.) are commonly used to denote degrees conferred by these universities where the potential for confusion exists, and institution names are given in this form in the Commonwealth Universities Yearbook.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] Abbreviations used for degrees vary between countries and institutions, e.g.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] MS indicates Master of Science in the US and places following American usage, but Master of Surgery in the UK and most Commonwealth countries, where the standard abbreviation for Master of Science is MSc.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] Common abbreviations include BA and MA for Bachelor and Master of Arts, BS/BSc and MS/MSc for Bachelor and Master of Science, MD for Doctor of Medicine and PhD for Doctor of Philosophy.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p01] Improvements in technology, the increasing use of the Internet worldwide, and the need for people to have flexible school schedules that enable them to work while attending school have led to a proliferation of online colleges that award associate's, bachelor's, master's, and doctoral degrees.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Bangladesh and India mostly follow the colonial era British system for the classification of degrees, however, Pakistan has recently switched to the US model of a two-year associate degree and a four-year bachelor's degree program.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] The arts, referring to the performing arts and literature, may confer a Bachelor of Arts (BA) and a Master of Arts (MA).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Management degrees are also classified under 'arts' but are nowadays considered a separate stream, with degrees of Bachelor of Business Administration (BBA) and Master of Business Administration (MBA).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Science refers to the basic sciences and natural science (Biology, Physics, Chemistry, etc.); the corresponding degrees are Bachelor of Science (BSc) and Master of Science (MSc).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Information Technology degrees are conferred specially in the field of computer science, and include Bachelor of Science in Information Technology (B.Sc.IT.) and Master of Science in Information Technology (M.Sc.IT.).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] The engineering degree in India follows two nomenclatures, Bachelor of Engineering (B.Eng.) and Bachelor of Technology (B.Tech.).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Both represent bachelor's degree in engineering.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] In Pakistan, engineering degrees are Bachelor of Engineering (B.E.) and Bachelor of Science in Engineering (B.S./B.Sc.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Both are the same in curriculum, duration and pattern, and differ only in nomenclature.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] The engineering degree in Bangladesh is a Bachelor of Science in Engineering (B.Sc.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Indonesia follows a higher education system that originated from the Dutch colonial period.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] However, over the years, Indonesia has transitioned from the Dutch degree classification system and developed its own academic distinctions by translating and adapting its degree structure.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] All degrees in Indonesia follow standardized regulations.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] The duration of each program is specified by Regulation of the Minister of Education and Culture of the Republic of Indonesia Number 3 of 2020 on National Standards of Higher Education.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] The regulation outlines the maximum duration and minimum credit requirements (Semester Credit Units or SKS) for each level of study without counting academic leave.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] The degree structure follows a standardized pattern, where XX represents the specific field of study.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Since a semester consists of 14 or 15 weeks of coursework and 1 or 2 weeks of exams, one SKS translates to an average of 40 hours of study per semester.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Comparatively, one European Credit Transfer and Accumulation System (ECTS) credit equals 28 hours of study, meaning that one Indonesian SKS is approximately equivalent to 1.5 ECTS.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Therefore, a bachelor's degree in Indonesia (minimum 144 SKS) is roughly equivalent to 216 ECTS, which surpasses the standard European requirement of 180 ECTS for a bachelor's degree.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] All degrees in Indonesia grant academic titles, which are often used in formal and social settings, including on unofficial documents such as marriage invitations.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Before Indonesia adopted its modern degree classification, the country used a system copied from the Dutch colonial academic structure, which in Netherlands remained extant to 2002.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] In this system, university students typically studied for five years before graduating.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] This structure was different from the modern four-year bachelor's (S1) degree, as it allowed graduates to proceed directly to a doctorate (S3) program without first obtaining a master's (S2) degree.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] This system included pre-nominal academic titles that have largely been phased out but are still recognized, for those who graduated before 1992.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Some of these titles are still in limited use today.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Doktorandus (Drs.) and Doktoranda (Dra.) originated from Latin, meaning "one who is to become a doctor." These titles indicated that the degree holder only needed to complete a dissertation to obtain a doctorate.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Until the 1960s, diplomas from Bandung Institute of Technology (ITB) explicitly stated that holders were entitled to pursue a doctorate upon defending a thesis.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] After the 1970s, ITB replaced Doktorandus and Insinyur (Engineer) titles with Sarjana (Bachelor) degrees.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] However, these titles remained granted and used until 1992 in other universities or institutes.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] By aligning with Anglo education standards, Indonesia transitioned to the B.Sc. - M.Sc. - Ph.D. model, similar to the Bologna Process.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Unlike the previous system, where five-year graduates could proceed directly to a Ph.D., students must now complete an S1 (Bachelor's) and S2 (Master's) before pursuing S3 (Doctorate).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Despite this transition, many pre-1992 graduates retained the use of their original titles granted upon their graduation, making formats such as Prof.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Drs. [Name] common among senior academics and professionals.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Sri Lanka, like many other commonwealth countries, follows the British system, but with its own distinctions.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Degrees are approved by the University Grants Commission.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Tunisia's educational grading system, ranging from elementary school to Ph.D. programs, operates on a scale of 0 to 20.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] The minimum score for passing is set at 10 out of 20.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] This numerical system exclusively evaluates a student's academic accomplishments, serving as the determinant for admission into advanced programs.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] For instance, a student's grades obtained for their bachelor's degree are considered when they apply for a Master's program.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Level 4 courses, which include the first year of a Bachelor's program or a Higher National Certificate (HNC), may allow students to enter directly into the second year of a Bachelor's program, provided that the course they completed is the same as the one they are applying for.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] In South Africa, grades (also known as "marks") are presented as a percentage, with anything below 50% considered a failure.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Students who receive a failing grade may have the opportunity to rewrite the exam, depending on the criteria established by their institution.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Degrees in almost any field of study can be pursued at one of the institutions in the country, with certain institutions being known for excelling in specific fields.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Major fields of study across the country include Arts, Commerce, Engineering, Law, Medicine, Science, and Theology.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] The South African Qualifications Authority (SAQA) has developed a credit-based system for degrees, with different levels of National Qualifications Framework (NQF) ratings corresponding to each degree level.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] For example, an undergraduate degree in Science is rated at NQF level 6, while an additional year of study in that discipline would result in an NQF level 8 (honours degree) rating.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] In Kenya, the first undergraduate degree is pursued after students have completed four years of secondary school education and attained at least a C+ (55–59%) on the Kenya Certificate of Secondary Education (KCSE).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Students pursuing a degree in engineering, such as B.Sc.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Electrical and Electronics Engineering, are required to join programs that are accredited by the Engineers Board of Kenya and the Commission for University Education.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] The B.Sc. degree in engineering typically takes five years to complete.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] A degree in medicine or surgery may take six to seven years, while a degree in education or management takes around four years.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] For students pursuing a master's degree, they must have completed an undergraduate degree and attained at least a second-class honours upper division (60–69%) or lower division plus at least two years of relevant experience.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Most master's degree programs take two years to complete.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] In an engineering master's degree program, students are typically required to publish at least one scientific paper in a peer-reviewed journal.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] To pursue a doctor of philosophy degree, students must have completed a relevant master's degree.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] They are required to carry out a supervised scientific study for a minimum of three years and publish at least two scientific first-author papers in peer-reviewed journals relevant to their area of study.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Currently, Kenya is implementing a Competency Based Curriculum (CBC) that follows a 2–6–3–3 education system to replace the existing 8–4–4 system which allows confirmation of undergraduate degrees upon successful completion.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] This system is gradually replacing the two-stage system previously used in some countries and is combined with other elements such as the European Credit Transfer and Accumulation System (ECTS) and the use of Diploma Supplements to make comparisons between qualifications easier.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] The European Higher Education Area (EHEA) was formally established in 2010 and, as of September 2016, has 50 members.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] The implementation of the various elements of the EHEA varies between countries.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Twenty-four countries have fully implemented a national qualifications framework, and a further ten have a framework but have not yet certified it against the overarching framework.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] In 38 countries, ECTS credits are used for all higher education programmes, and 31 countries have fully implemented diploma supplements.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Only 11 countries have included all the major points of the Lisbon Recognition Convention in national legislation.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Since 2008, the European Union has been developing the European Qualifications Framework (EQF).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] This is an eight-level framework designed to allow cross-referencing of the various national qualifications frameworks.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] While it is not specific to higher education, the top four levels (5–8) correspond to the short cycle, first cycle, second cycle, and third cycle of the EHEA.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] The two-cycle degree system was phased out by 2010, with a few exceptions.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] However, some of the established degree naming has been preserved, allowing universities to award the "Diplom-Ingenieur" (and for a while also the "Magister") to graduates of the new-style Master programmes.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] While higher education is regulated by the three communities of Belgium, all have common and comparable systems of degrees that were adapted to the Bologna structure during the 2000s.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] The primary 3-cycle structure is called BMD (Bachelor-Master-Doctorate; French: *Bachelier-Master-Doctorat* or Dutch: *Bachelor-Master-Doctoraat*).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] In the first cycle, the Bachelor's degree is issued after 180 ECTS (3 years, EQF level 6).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Other first cycle degrees include the one-year Advanced Bachelor's degree degree (French: *Bachelier de spécialisation*, lit.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] 'Specialized Bachelor'; Dutch: *Bachelor-na-bachelor*, lit.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] 'Bachelor-after-bachelor') and the Brevet (in the French-speaking Community only) for short-cycle higher education programmes.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Bachelor's degrees are followed in the second cycle (EQF level 7) by Master's degrees that last two years, completing an extra 120 ECTS credits.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] The master's degree can be followed by an Advanced Master's degree (French: *Master de spécialisation*, lit.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] 'Specialized Master'; Dutch: *Master-na-master*, lit.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] 'Master-after-master') that lasts one year (60 ECTS).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] The Czech Republic has implemented the Bologna process, and functionally has three degrees: Bachelor (3 years), Master (2 years after Bachelor) and Doctor (4 years after Master).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] The Czech Republic also has voluntary academic titles called "small doctorates" (e.g.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] RNDr. for natural sciences, PhDr. for philosophy, JUDr. for law etc.) which are achieved after passing an additional exam.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Medical students do not get bachelor's or master's degrees, but instead attend a six-year program and obligatory exam they achieve the title MUDr.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] (equivalent to MD degree in the United States of America), or MDDr. for dentists and MVDr. for veterinary physicians.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] They can also get a "big doctorate" (Ph.D.) after another three or four years of study.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Bachelor's degrees, master's degrees and small doctorates in the form of letters (Bc., Mgr., Ing., ...) are listed before the person's name, and Doctor's degrees (Ph.D.) are listed after name (e.g.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] The Czech Republic previously had more degrees that were awarded.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Before the adoption of the Bologna Process, the lowest degree that would normally be studied at universities in Denmark was equivalent to a master's degree (*kandidatgrad*).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Officially, a bachelor's degree was always obtained after 3 years' university studies.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Various medium-length (2–4 years) professional degrees have been adopted, so they now have status as professional bachelor's degrees of varying length.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] As opposed to academic bachelor's degrees, they are considered to be "applied" degrees.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] A professional bachelor's degree is 180, 210, or 240 ECTS-points.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Historically, the Finnish higher education system is derived from the German system.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] The current system of higher education comprises two types of higher education institutions, the universities and the polytechnics, many of whom refer to themselves as universities of applied sciences (UAS).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] With the exception of a few fields, such as medicine and dentistry, the Finnish system of higher education degrees is in compliance with the Bologna process.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Universities award bachelor's degrees (*kandidaatti / kandidat*), Master's degrees (*maisteri / magister*) and doctoral degrees (*lisensiaatin tutkinto / licentiat examen* and *tohtorin tutkinto / doktorexamen*).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] In most fields, the system of doctoral degrees is two-tier, the degree of licentiate is an independent academic degree but completing the degree of doctor does not require completion of a licentiate degree.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] The polytechnics (universities of applied sciences) have the right to award bachelor's and master's degrees; the degree titles are distinct from the titles used for university degrees.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] In general, students who are admitted to bachelor studies at a university have the right to continue to studies at master level.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] At polytechnics, the right to continue to master-level studies has to be applied for separately and there is also a work experience requirement.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] The majority of master's degree holders have graduated from university.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] The degrees awarded by the universities and polytechnics are at par by law, but the content and orientation of studies is different.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] A master's degree obtained at a polytechnic gives the same academic right to continue studies at doctoral level as a master's degree obtained at a university.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] The French national education system makes a distinction between a *diplôme national* ("national degree") and *diplôme universitaire* ("university degree").
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] The former, which are considered to have a higher status, are controlled by the state and issued by universities on behalf of the responsible ministry; the latter are controlled and granted by the universities themselves.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Additionally, private universities and schools may be recognised by the state with a *diplôme visé* ("recognised degree") and then, after five years of recognition, have their degrees validated by the state, the validation having to be renewed every six years.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Historically, academic degrees were orientated towards research, and the vocational education system awarded only diplomas.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Since the implementation of the Bologna Process in France, the degree-granting system is being simplified: schools continue to grant their own diplomas, but the state's recognition in degree awarding is more important than before.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] However, in France there are diplomas that are not recognised as degrees, such as specific diplomas designed by colleges (*écoles supérieures*), like the *mastère spécialisé* (accredited by the *Conférence des Grandes Écoles* but not automatically by the French Government).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Since 2002, *grande école* diplomas have been able to award a university degree, such as the Sciences Po *Bachelor*, which is a state-accredited diploma that awards a bachelor's degree (*Licence* in French).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] The recognised degrees are in three levels, following the Qualifications Framework of the European Higher Education Area.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] These are the *licence* (first level), *master* (second level) and *doctorat* (third level).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] All licence degrees take 3 years (180 ECTS credits) and all master's degrees take 2 years (120 ECTS credits).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] There are also 5-year (300 ECTS credits) engineer's degrees, which are master's degrees.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] In addition to the doctorate, which is always a research degree, the *Diplôme d'Etat de docteur en médicine* and the *Diplôme d'Etat de docteur vétérinaire* are third level qualifications and recognized as level 7 in EQF.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] Traditionally in Germany, students studied for four to six years and then graduated with either a *Magister* degree (usually in subjects like humanities, linguistics or the arts) or a *Diplom* degree (typically in fields such as natural sciences, economics, or engineering).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p02] These qualifications were usually the first and highest academic degrees students earned before a doctorate.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Both Magister and Diplom degrees from universities required a final thesis and are generally considered equivalent to a modern master’s degree.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] However, the Diplom awarded by a *Fachhochschule* (university of applied sciences) is usually considered comparable to a bachelor’s degree.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] A different type of qualification in Germany is the *Staatsexamen* (state examination).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] This is not an academic degree but a government licensing examination required for certain professions, such as doctors, teachers, lawyers, judges, and pharmacists.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Students typically study at university for three to six years before taking the first Staatsexamen, depending on their field.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] After passing the first Staatsexamen, candidates in fields like law and teaching must complete a practical training period called the *Vorbereitungsdienst* (preparatory service), which usually lasts about two years.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] They then take a second Staatsexamen, which tests their practical skills.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] In some cases, students of law or pharmacy can choose to graduate with a master’s degree instead of taking the first Staatsexamen.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Since 1999, Germany has replaced its traditional university degrees with bachelor’s and master’s degrees as part of the Bologna process.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] This reform aimed to make degrees more comparable internationally and to shorten the overall time students spend in higher education, as older programs often took five years or more to complete.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Today, students typically complete a bachelor’s degree followed by a master’s degree; the first usually taking 3 years, and the latter taking 18 months to 2 years.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Some universities resisted the change, but by the end of 2007 all institutions were required to adopt the new system.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Degree programs that lead to a Staatsexamen (state examination), such as those in law or medicine, were generally not converted to the bachelor’s/master’s system.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] In Germany, doctoral degrees are awarded with different titles depending on the subject area.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Examples include Doktor der Naturwissenschaften (Doctor of Natural Sciences), Doktor der Rechtswissenschaften (Doctor of Law), Doktor der Medizin (Doctor of Medicine), and Doktor der Philosophie (Doctor of Philosophy).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] In German-speaking countries, it is common for people to list multiple doctorates and honorary titles, and sometimes even use them in formal address.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Students who have completed a Diplom, Magister, master’s degree, or Staatsexamen can usually continue on to a doctorate.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] In some cases, particularly strong bachelor’s graduates may also be admitted directly to a doctoral program after passing an aptitude assessment set by the university.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Doctoral degrees (such as Dr. rer. nat. or Dr. phil.) are the highest academic qualifications in Germany and are typically based on independent research.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] (Doctor of Medicine): medical doctors often complete their doctoral thesis shortly after finishing their studies, and it may involve less independent research compared to doctorates in other fields.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Unlike some countries such as the United Kingdom, Germany does not have a system of “higher doctorates” (such as the Doctor of Science).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The Habilitation is an additional qualification beyond the doctorate, although it is not an academic degree.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] It demonstrates the ability to carry out advanced research and teach at the university level.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] To obtain a Habilitation, candidates usually write a second thesis (called a *Habilitationsschrift*) or submit a collection of significant research publications.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Once completed, the qualification is sometimes abbreviated as “habil.” after a person’s name.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Traditionally, the Habilitation was required to become a *Privatdozent* (a university lecturer qualified to teach independently) and to pursue a professorship.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Today, universities no longer require it, although it can still be an advantage in more traditional academic fields.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] In Greece access to university is possible after national exams (Panhellenic Exams).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Ireland operates under a National Framework of Qualifications (NFQ).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The school-leaving qualification attained by students is called the Leaving Certificate.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] It is considered as Level 4–5 in the framework.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] This qualification is the traditional route of entry into third-level education.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] There are also Level 5 qualifications in certain vocational subjects (e.g.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Level 5 Certificate in Restaurant Operations) awarded by the Further Education and Training Awards Council (FETAC).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Advanced Certificates at Level 6 are also awarded by FETAC.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] These are completed in institutes of technology or universities.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] In Italy access to university is possible after gaining the *Diploma di Maturità* at 19 years of age, following 5 years of study in a specific high school focused on certain subjects (e.g.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] After gaining the diploma one can enter university and enrol in any curriculum (e.g. physics, medicine, chemistry, engineering, architecture): all high school diplomas allow access to any university curriculum, although most universities have pre-admission tests.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] In addition to academic degrees, many professional qualifications are tied to the QTI at the different levels.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The first level, tied to the first cycle of the Bologna Process, covers the *laurea* (bachelor's degree) in universities and the *Diploma accademico di primo livello* in AFAM institutions.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The *laurea* is obtained after three years of study (180 ECTS credits) and confers the academic title of *dottore*; the older university qualifications at this level took two to three years, with the three-year courses conferring the title of *dottore*.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The second level, tied to the second cycle of the Bologna Process, covers the *laurea magistrale* and the *laurea specialistica* of university institutions, and the *Diploma accademico di secondo livello* of AFAM institutions.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The old *Diploma di laurea* is mapped to this level.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The *Laurea magistrale* and the *laurea specialistica* are obtained after two further years of study (120 ECTS credits) and give the academic title of *dottore magistrale*.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The old *Diploma di laurea* took four to six years but was accessed directly from school, with a possible reduction by one year for those with a related *diploma* and also granted the title of *dottore magistrale*.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The third level, tied to the third cycle of the Bologna Process, covers the *Dottorato di ricerca* from university institutions and the *Diploma accademico di formazione alla ricerca* from AFAM institutions.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The old *Dottorato di ricerca* and *Diploma di specializzazione* are tied to this level.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The *Dottorato di ricerca*, under both new and old systems, takes a minimum of three years after the *laurea magistralie/specialistica*, and gives the academic titles of *Dottore di Ricerca (Dott.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The old *Diploma di specializzazione* took two to six years and gave the academic title of *Specialista*.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The *Diploma di specializzazione*, which is offered in a few specific professions, takes two to six years and gives the title of *specialista*.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The *Diploma di perfezionamento* is a university certificate, aimed at professional training or in specific fields of study, which usually takes one year; it is not allocated a level in the framework.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] AFAM institutions may offer the *Diploma di perfezionamento o Master* and *Diploma accademico di specializzazione*.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] These are one-year and two-year qualifications, respectively, and may be offered at the second cycle or third cycle level, distinguished by adding *(I)* or *(II)* after the qualification name.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Higher schools for language mediators offer the *Diploma di mediatore linguistico*, a first-cycle degree that takes three years (180 ECTS credits), and which gives access to the *laurea specialistica*.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Specialisation institutes/schools in psychotherapy offer the *Diploma di specializzazione in psicoterapia*, a third-cycle qualification that takes at least four years and requires a *laurea magistrale/specialistica* in either psychology or medicine and surgery, along with professional registration.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] In the Netherlands, the structure of academic studies was altered significantly in 1982 when the "Tweefasenstructuur" (Two Phase Structure) was introduced by the Dutch Minister of Education, Wim Deetman.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] With this structure an attempt was made to standardise all the different studies and to have them conform to similar timetables.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] An additional effect was that students would be forced to produce results within a preset time-frame or otherwise discontinue their studies.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The two-phase structure has been adapted to a bachelor-master structure as a result of the Bologna process.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] In order for a Dutch student to get access to a university education, the student must complete a six-year pre-university secondary education called *voorbereidend wetenschappelijk onderwijs* (VWO).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] There are other routes possible, but only if the educational level of the applicant is comparable to that at the end of the standard two levels is access to university education granted.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] For some studies, specific end levels or disciplines are required, e.g., graduating without having studied physics, biology and chemistry will make it impossible to study medicine.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] People 21 years old, or older, who do not have the required entrance diplomas, may opt for an entrance exam to be admitted to a higher-educational curriculum.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] In this exam, they have to prove their command of disciplines considered necessary for pursuing such study.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] After 1 September 2002, they would be thus admitted to a Bachelor's curriculum, not to a Master's curriculum.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] For some disciplines in the Netherlands, a governmentally determined limited access is in place (although under political review for abolishment, as of February 2011).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] This limits the number of applicants to a specific course of study, thus trying to control the number of future graduates.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The disciplines most renowned for their numerus clausus are medicine and dentistry.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Every year a combination of the highest pre-university graduation grades and some additional conditions determine who can start such a numerus clausus course of study and who can not.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Almost all Dutch universities are government supported, with only a few privately owned universities in existence (i.e. one in business and all others in theology).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Leiden University is the oldest, founded in 1575.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] For medical students the "doctorandus" degree is not equivalent to the European Anglo Saxon postgraduate research degree in medicine, of MD (Medical Doctor).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Besides the title doctorandus, the graduates of the Curius curriculum may also bear the title *arts* (physician).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The doctorandus in medicine title is granted after four years (nominal time) of the Curius curriculum, while the title physician is granted after six years (nominal time) of that curriculum.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The Dutch physician title is equal to a MSc degree according to the Bologna process and can be compared with the MBBS in the UK degree system and the North American MD, but not the UK MD degree, which is a research degree.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] One-on-one equivalence or interchangeability of the Dutch medical title and MD is often suggested.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] However, officially the MD title is not known, nor legal to use, in the Netherlands.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The correct notation for a Dutch physician who completed his or her medical studies, but did not pursue a doctoral (PhD-like) study is "drs." (e.g.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Jansen, arts*) and not "dr." in medicine, which is often used incorrectly.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] However, like in the United Kingdom, physicians holding these degrees are referred to as 'Doctor' by courtesy.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] In the Netherlands, there is the informal title *dokter* for physicians, but not *doctor* (dr.), unless they also earn such adegree by completing a PhD curriculum.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Furthermore, the *doctorandus* degree does not give a medical student the right to treat patients; for this a minimum of two years of additional study (internship) is required.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] After obtaining a Medical Board registration, Dutch physicians must work an additional two to six years in a field of expertise to become a registered medical specialist.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Dutch surgeons commonly are only granted access to surgical training and positions after obtaining a doctorate (PhD) successfully.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] In recent years, the six-year (nominal time) old Curius curriculum (which offered the titles doctorandus and physician) has been replaced with a three-year (nominal time) Bachelor Curius+ followed by a three-year (nominal time) Master Curius+.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Those who had already begun their old-style Curius curriculum before that will still have to complete it as a six-year study (nominal time).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] A doctorandus in law uses the title *meester* (master, abbreviated as *mr.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Jansen*) instead of drs., and some courses of study, such as in technology and agriculture< grant the title *ingenieur* (engineer, noted as *ir.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] These titles as equivalent to an LL.M (the title "mr.") and to a MSc (the title "ir.") and if gotten before 1 September 2002, from a recognized Dutch university, may be rendered as M (from Master) behind one's name, instead of using the typical Dutch honorifics before one's name.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] However, this M is hardly used in favor of the typical Dutch titles ("drs.", "ir.", "mr."), or MSc, MA or LLM.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Since 1 September 2002, Dutch universities offer specific BSc, BA or LLB studies followed by MSc, MA or LLM studies, thus integrating into the international scientific community, offering lectures, other classes, seminars or complete curricula in English instead of Dutch.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] According to their field of study, MSc graduates may use either ir. or drs. before their names; MA graduates may use drs. before their name; LLM graduates may use mr. before their names, but only if they received such degrees from recognized Dutch universities.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Not uncommonly, the Dutch "drs." abbreviation can cause much confusion in other countries, since it is perceived as a person who has a PhD in multiple disciplines.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] In the Netherlands, the degree MPhil was not awarded after 2009 as the Universiteiten van Nederland refused to recognize the MPhils awarded by Leiden University.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] After successfully obtaining a "drs.", "ir." or "mr." degree, a student has the opportunity to follow a further, promotional course of study (informally called PhD) to eventually obtain a doctorate and subsequently the title "doctor".
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Promotion studies are ideally structured according to a preset time schedule of 4 to 6 years, during which the student has to be mentored by at least one professor.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The promotion study has to be concluded with at least a scientific thesis, which has to be defended to "a gathering of his/her peers", in practice the board of the faculty with guest professors from other faculties or universities added.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] More and more common—and, in some disciplines, even mandatory—is that the student write, and have accepted for publication by peer-reviewed journals, original scientific work.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The number of publications required is often debated and varies considerably between the various disciplines.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] However, in all disciplines the student is obligated to produce and publish a dissertation or thesis in book form.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] All current Dutch academic programs are offered under the Anglo-Saxon bachelor/master structure.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] It takes three years to earn a bachelor's degree and another one or two years to earn a master's degree.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] There are three official academic bachelor titles (BA, BSc and LLB) and three official master titles (MA, MSc and LLM).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] These academic titles are protected by the Dutch government.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] After obtaining a doctorate, Dutch doctors may bear either the title dr.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] (lower case) before, or the letter D following, their name, but not both simultaneously.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] There is no notation signifying the specific discipline in which the doctorate is obtained.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] As of 1 January 2021, the title 'PhD' and post-nominal degree 'PhD' can also be used, and these are also legally protected.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Stacking of titles, as seen in countries such as Germany (Prof.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Gruber), is highly uncommon in the Netherlands and not well received culturally.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Those who have multiple doctoral titles may use dr.mult. before their name, but this is seldom seen in practice.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The *honoris causa* doctors may use dr.h.c. before their name.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Combining different Dutch titles, especially in different disciplines, is allowed, however, (e.g. mr. dr.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The use of the combination ir. ing. is frequent, indicating one holds a HBO, vocational, or professional engineering degree "ing.", together with an academic engineering degree "ir.".
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] What is not allowed is, after obtaining a doctorate, using dr. drs.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] A combination of a Dutch title with an international title is not allowed, except for some limited number of international professional titles.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Thus, one should choose either one's classical Dutch title or use the shortcut provided by the law following one's name (since 1 September 2002 it is the other way around: those who hold Dutch degrees as MSc, LLM or MA may optionally use the old-style shortcuts before their names).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] "*Doctors*" (dr.) can proceed to teach at universities as "universitair docent" (UD – assistant professor).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] With time, experience and achievement, this can evolve to a position as "universitair hoofddocent" (UHD – associate professor).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Officially an UHD still works under the supervision of a "hoogleraar" (professor), the head of the department.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] However, this is not a given; it is also possible that a department is headed by a "plain" doctor, based on knowledge, achievement and expertise.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The position of "hoogleraar" is the highest possible scientific position at a university and equivalent to the US "full" professor.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The Dutch professor's title, noted as *prof.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Jansen* or *professor Jansen*, is connected to one's employment.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] This means that, should the professor leave the university, he or she also loses the privilege to use the title of professor.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Retired professors are an exception and may continue to note the title in front of their name, or use the title emeritus professor (em. prof.).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] People who switch to a non-university job lose their professorial title and are only allowed to use the "dr." abbreviation.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Unlike some other European countries, such as Germany, Dutch academic titles are used rarely outside academia, hold no value in everyday life, and typically are not listed on official documentation (e.g. passport, drivers license, (governmental) communication).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Dutch academic titles, however, are legally protected and can only be used by graduates from Dutch institutions of higher education.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Illegal use is considered a misdemeanor and is subject to legal prosecution.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Holders of foreign degrees, therefore, need special permission before being able to use a recognised Dutch title, but they are free to use their own foreign title (untranslated).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] In practice, the Public Department does not prosecute the illegal use of a protected title (the Netherlands applies prosecutorial discretion, so some known criminal uses are not prosecuted).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Prior to 1980, there were around 50 different degrees and corresponding educational programs within the Norwegian higher education system.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Degrees had titles that included the gender based Latin term *candidatus/candidata*.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The second part of the title usually consisted of a Latin word corresponding to the profession or training.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] (Candidatus Magisterii) required 4 to 5 years, Cand.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] (Candidatus Realium) required 6 years of study and a scientific thesis in a select set of scientific disciplines (realia).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Over the years these were replaced gradually with degrees that were more and more internationally comparable programs and corresponding titles.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] These degrees were all retired in 2003 in favour of an international system.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The reform of higher education in Norway, *Kvalitetsreformen* ("The Quality Reform"), was passed in the Norwegian Parliament, the Storting, in 2001 and carried out during the 2003/2004 academic year.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] It introduced standard periods of study and the titles *master* and *bachelor (baccalaureus)*.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The system differentiates between a free master's degree and a master's degree in technology.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The latter corresponds to the former *sivilingeniør* degree (not to be confused with a degree in civil engineering, which is but one of many degrees linked to the title *sivilingeniør*, which is still in use for new graduates who can choose to also use the old title).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] All pre-2001 doctoral degree titles were replaced with the title "Philosophical Doctor degree", written *philosophiæ doctor* (instead of the traditional *doctor philosophiæ*).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The title dr. philos. is a substantially higher degree than the PhD and is reserved for those who qualify for such a degree without participating in an organized doctoral degree program.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] In Poland, the system is similar to the German one.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Since 1992, Russian higher education has introduced a multilevel system, enabling higher education institutions to award and issue Bachelor of Science and Master of Science degrees.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] In Russia, Ukraine and some other former USSR republics educational degrees are awarded after finishing a college education.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] There are several levels of education that one must choose in the 2nd and 3rd year of college, usually in the 3rd year of study.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] A specialist degree is awarded after 5 years of college (4 + 1).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] A Master's (Magister) degree is awarded after 6 years of college (4 + 2).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] But a Specialist degree can appear equivalent to Magister degree by reason of taking an equivalent amount of time.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Usually Specialist or Magister degrees incorporate the bachelor's degrees in them, but only the high-level degree is given on the final diploma.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Specialist and Magister degrees require taking final state exams and producing written work on practical application of studied skills or research thesis (usually 70–100 pages) and is roughly equivalent to a master's degree.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The first-level academic degree is called *Candidate of Sciences* ("Kandidat Nauk").
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Finally, there is a *Doctor of Sciences* ("Doktor Nauk") degree in Russia and some former USSR academic environments.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] This degree is granted for contributions in a certain field (formally – who established new direction or new field in science).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] It requires discovery of new phenomenon or development of new theory or essential development of new direction, etc.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] There is no equivalent of this "doctor of sciences" degree in the US academic system.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] It is roughly equivalent to Habilitation in Germany, France, Austria and some other European countries.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] In countries with a two-tier system of doctoral degrees, the degree of *Candidate of Sciences* should be considered for recognition at the level of the first doctoral degree.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] According to *Guidelines for the recognition of Russian qualifications in the other countries*, in countries with a two-tier system of doctoral degrees, the degree of *Doktor Nauk* should be considered for recognition at the level of the second doctoral degree.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] In countries in which only one doctoral degree exists, the degree of *Doktor Nauk* should be considered for recognition at the level of this degree.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] LL.D. to *Candidate of Sciences of Legal Science*.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Spain's higher-education legal framework includes official and accredited education, as well as non-official education.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] In Spain, accreditation of official university study programmes is regulated by law and monitored by governmental agencies responsible for verifying their quality and suitability for official approval and accreditation.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Official professional study programmes lead to degree qualifications (*Títulos*) with full academic and professional rights.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Master's Degree (*Master Universitario*) – 60 to 120 ECTS Credits in 1–2 years.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Doctoral degree PhD (*Doctorado*) – in 3–4 years.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Accredited bachelor's degrees and master's degrees qualifications will always be described as *Grado* and *Master Universitario*.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] These qualifications comply with the European Higher Education Area (EHEA) framework.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Officially approved and accredited university study programmes by law must implement this framework in order to attain and retain accreditation in Spain.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Not all EHEA-compliant study programmes in Spain are officially approved or accredited by government agencies.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Some universities offer proprietary study programmes as alternatives for a variety of reasons: serving the continuing education market for individual self-advancement and also providing higher education to individuals who have failed to acquire bachelor's degree qualifications.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The main reason for offering these alternative studies, though, is the complex bureaucratic process required to receive the approval of specific titles, in particular when it refers to new studies or studies about matters that do not fit with the official studies.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] For historical reasons, the academic system has been very much under the control of the state, and private universities are still regarded with as a threat to the state system.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] These programmes fall within the category of "non officially approved and accredited" or *estudios no oficiales*, and they confer no academic or professional rights.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] This means that they do not entitle the bearer to claim to have any specific academic or professional qualifications, as far as the Spanish authorities are concerned.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] However, there may be private agreements to recognize the titles.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Universities offering non-official study programmes are legally bound to clearly differentiate between officially-approved and non-officially-approved qualifications.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Non-accredited master's degrees will be described as just *Master*, without the accompanying *Universitario*.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Certain non-officially approved and accredited study programmes may acquire a positive reputation.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] However, neither professional associations, government agencies, judiciary authorities, nor universities – other than the study programme provider – are obliged to recognize non-official qualifications in any way.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] All study programmes must be accredited by ANECA prior to their inclusion in the RUCT.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The RUCT records all officially approved universities and their bachelor's degrees, master's degrees and PhDs and each and every one of the officially approved and accredited study programmes.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Universities are assigned a specific number Code (*Código*) by the RUCT.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The same study programme may acquire different codes as it progresses through various stages of official approval by local and central governments.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Prospective students should check the RUCT Code awarded to the study programme of their interest at every stage of their enquiries concerning degrees in Spain.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] ANECA makes recommendations regarding procedures, staffing levels, quality of teaching, resources available to students and continuity or loss of accreditation.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The ANECA Registry records all events in the life of an officially approved and accredited study programme or a university.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The ANECA Registry Search Facility may be the simplest and safest way to verify the status of all officially approved and accredited study programmes in Spain.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] It is also possible to track qualifications by using the search facility that several Autonomous Communities' own accreditation agencies offer.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The qualifications framework for higher education MECES is the reference framework adopted in Spain in order to structure degree levels.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Not all universities offer degrees named exactly the same, even if they have similar academic and professional effects.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Each university may present proposals for the study programme considered to meet professional and academic demand.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] The proposal will consist of a report linking the study programme being considered and the proposed qualification to be awarded.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] This report will be assessed by ANECA and sent for the Consejo de Universidades Españolas.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] If the *Consejo* agrees with ANECA's approval, it will be included in the RUCT and ANECA registries.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] All bachelor's and master's degrees accredited by ANECA bestow full academic and professional rights in accordance with new and previous laws.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Professional-practice law in Spain is currently under revision.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Before the Bologna Process, the academic degree of a Licentiate was reached after 4 or 5 years of study.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Depending on the official language of the university, it was called *Lizentiat* (German), *Licence* (French) or *licenza* (Italian) and, according to the Bologna reform, is today considered equivalent to a master's degree.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] A Licentiate with a predefined qualification gave access to the last stage of a further two or more years of studies (depending on the field) for a doctoral degree.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Apart from this, most universities offered a postgraduate diploma requiring up to two years of study.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] French-speaking universities called them *diplôme d'études approfondies* DEA or DESS, the Italian-speaking university *post laurea* and German-speaking universities mostly *Nachdiplomstudium* (NDS).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Today the federal legislation defines these postgraduate diplomas (60 ECTS credits) as Master of Advanced Studies (MAS) or Executive Master of Business Administration (EMBA) degrees.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Universities may also offer the possibility to gain a diploma in advanced studies (DAS, less than 60 ECTS credits).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] These degrees do not normally give access to a doctoral programme.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Turkish education system has been mostly compatible with the Bologna process before and immediately after adoption.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] New graduates of a bachelor's program from Turkish law faculties are required to enter a legal licensing examination from 2022 onwards, in order to use all the rights to the extent that has been granted by the related laws.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p03] Such requirement does not exist for other degree holders.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] An academic degree is protected under UK law.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] All valid UK degrees are awarded by universities or other degree-awarding bodies whose powers to do so are recognised by the UK government; hence they are known as "recognised bodies".
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] The standard first degree in England, Northern Ireland and Wales is the bachelor's degree conferred with honours.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Usually this is a Bachelor of Arts (BA) or a Bachelor of Science (BSc) degree.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Other variants exist: for example, Bachelor of Education or Bachelor of Laws.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] It usually takes three years to read for a bachelor's degree.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Candidates who have not achieved the standard for the award of honours may be admitted without honours to the "ordinary" bachelor's degree if they have met the required standard for this lesser qualification (also referred to as a "pass degree").
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Standard levels for each of these classes are 70%+ for a first, 60–69% for a 2:1, 50–59% for a 2:2, 40–49% for a 3rd and 30%+ for a pass degree, although this can vary by institution (e.g. the Open University).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] The foundation degree is a qualification, lower than bachelor's level, awarded following a two-year programme of study that is usually vocational in nature.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] The foundation degree can be awarded by a university or college of higher education that has been granted foundation-degree-awarding powers by the UK government.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] This degree is comparable to an associate degree in the United States.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] The universities of Oxford and Cambridge award honorary Master of Arts (MA) degrees to graduates of their bachelor's programmes, following a specified period of time.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] This is comparable to the practice of the ancient universities in Scotland awarding an MA for a first degree and arguably reflects the rigorous standards expected of their graduates.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Master's degrees such as Master of Arts or Master of Science are typically awarded to students who have undertaken at least a year of full-time postgraduate study, which may require study and involve an element of research.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Degrees such as Master of Philosophy (MPhil) or Master of Letters/Literature (MLitt) are likely to be awarded for postgraduate study involving original research.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] A student undertaking a master's would normally be expected to already hold a bachelor's degree in a relevant subject, hence the possibility of reaching the master's level in one year.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Some universities award a master's as a first degree following an integrated programme of study (an 'integrated master's degree').
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] These degrees are usually designated by the subject, such as Master of Engineering for engineering, Master of Physics for physics, Master of Mathematics for mathematics and so on; it usually takes four years to read for them.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Graduation to these degrees is always with honours.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Master of Engineering in particular has now become the standard first degree in engineering at the top UK universities, replacing the older Bachelor of Engineering.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] The Master of Business Administration (MBA) degree is highly valued by those seeking to advance in business as managers and decision makers.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Doctoral degrees or doctorates, such as the Doctor of Philosophy degree (PhD or DPhil) or Doctor of Education (EdD or DEd), are awarded following a programme of original research that contributes new knowledge within the context of the student's discipline.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Doctoral degrees usually take three years full-time.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Therefore, in the UK it may only take seven years to progress from undergraduate to earning a doctorate – in some cases six, since having a master's is not always a precondition for embarking on a doctoral degree.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] This contrasts with nine years in the United States, reflecting differences in the educational systems.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Some doctorates, such as the Doctor of Clinical Psychology (DClinPsy) qualification, confirm competence to practice in particular professions.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] UK post-secondary qualifications are defined at different levels, with levels 1–3 denoting further education and levels 4–8 denoting higher education.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Within this structure, a foundation degree is at level 5; a bachelor's degree at level 6; a master's degree at level 7; and a doctoral degree at level 8.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Full information about the expectations for different types of UK degrees is published by the Quality Assurance Agency for Higher Education.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] See also graduate certificate, graduate diploma, postgraduate certificate, postgraduate diploma and British degree abbreviations.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] The standard first degree for students studying arts or humanities in Scotland is either a Bachelor of Arts or a Master of Arts (the latter traditionally awarded by the Ancient Universities of Scotland for a first degree in an arts/humanities subject).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] The standard undergraduate degree for natural and social science subjects is the Bachelor of Science.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Students can work towards a first degree at either ordinary or honours level.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] A general or ordinary degree (BA/MA or BSc) takes three years to complete; an honours degree (BA/MA Hons or BSc Hons) takes four years.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] The ordinary degree need not be in a specific subject, but can involve study across a range of subjects within (and sometimes beyond) the relevant faculty, in which case it may also be called a general degree.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] If a third year or junior honours subject is included, the ordinary degree in that named discipline is awarded.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] The honours degree involves two years of study at a sub-honours level in which a range of subjects within the relevant faculty are studied and then two years of study at honours level which is specialised in a single field (for example classics, history, chemistry, biology, etc.).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Not all universities in Scotland adhere to this; in some, one studies in several subjects within a faculty for three years and can then specialise in two areas and attain a joint honours degree in fourth year.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] This also reflects the broader scope of the final years of Scottish secondary education, where traditionally five Highers are studied, compared to (typically) three English or Welsh A-Levels.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] The Higher is a one-year qualification, as opposed to the two years of A-Levels, which accounts for Scottish honours degrees being a year longer than those in England.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Advanced Highers add an optional final year of secondary education, bringing students up to the level of their A-Level counterparts – students with strong A-Levels or Advanced Highers may be offered entry directly into the second year at Scottish universities.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Students who complete all the requirements for an honours degree, but who do not receive sufficient merit to be awarded third-class honours, may be awarded a *Special Degree* (ordinary degree – bachelor's level SCQF Level 9).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] In most respects, the criteria for awarding qualifications at honours level and above are the same as in the rest of the UK (see above under England, Wales and Northern Ireland).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Postgraduate qualifications are not designated Master of Arts, as in the rest of the UK, as this is an undergraduate degree.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Postgraduate degrees in arts and humanities subjects are usually designated Master of Letters (M.Litt.) or, in natural and social sciences, Master of Science (M.Sc.).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Non-doctoral postgraduate research degrees are usually designated Master of Philosophy (M.Phil.) or Master of Research (M.Res.).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] The postgraduate teaching qualification is the Postgraduate Diploma in Education (PGDE).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] In Canada, education is the responsibility of the provinces and territories, rather than the federal government.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] However, all of Canada follows the three-level bachelor's-master's-doctorate system common to the Anglophone world, with a few variations.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] A common framework for degrees was agreed between the provinces and territories in 2007.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Bachelor's degrees take normally three to four years, more commonly three years in Quebec (where they follow on from college courses rather than directly from secondary education).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Outside Quebec, three-year bachelor's degrees are normally ordinary degrees, while four-year bachelor's degrees are honours degrees; an honours degree is normally needed for further study at the master's level.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Master's degrees take one to three years (in Quebec they normally take one and a half to two years).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Doctorates take a minimum of three years.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Alone among Canadian provinces and territories, British Columbia offers two-year associate degrees, allowing credit to be transferred into a four-year bachelor's program.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] In Canada, first professional degrees such as DDS, MD, PharmD and LLB or JD are considered bachelor's level qualifications, despite their often being named as if they were doctorates.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] In the province of Quebec, the majority of students must attend college prior to entering university.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Upon completion of a two-year pre-university program, such as in sciences or humanities, or a three-year technical program, such as nursing or computer science, college graduates obtain a *college diploma*, which is a prerequisite for access to university-level studies.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Although these college programs are typical, they are not offered in every institution in the province.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Moreover, while a few other pre-university programs with various concentrations exist, many other technical/career programs are available, depending on the college of choice.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] For example, Dawson College in Montreal has nearly sixty different programs leading to a college diploma.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Special programs, such as physical rehabilitation therapy, are offered in some colleges as well.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] A similar option is offered for college nursing graduates as they can pursue their studies in university to obtain a Bachelor of Nursing in two years (rather than the usual three or four years, depending on whether the student has completed a college diploma in Quebec).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Education in Mexico follows a three-degree system similar to that of Canada and the US.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] The pre-university academic level is the *bachillerato* (also called *preparatoria*), similar to high school.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] They can also get the degree of "ingenieria" or "medico" as an engineer or MD, respectively.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] After receiving the *licenciatura*, students may take extra courses called *diplomados* (similar to a certification but issued by a university).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] These courses last 4–12 months and are a means to further study without continuing to the next degree level, and are usually to demonstrate that students are staying up-to-date in their fields.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Most students stay at this level, but some choose to continue to the *maestría*, equivalent to the master's degree.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Study at the *maestría* level takes 1–3 years and mandates completion of a thesis.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Post-graduate students in Mexico typically enter a master's program after a few years in the workforce and often continue working while studying.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Traditionally, students who have completed the *maestria* may continue on to the *doctorado* or the doctorate.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Doctoral study typically lasts 3–4 years.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] In recent years this schemes has become flexible such that in some PhD programmes, students are accepted before, or not completing, the course of study for a master's.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] In the United States, since the late 19th century, the threefold degree system of bachelor's, master's, and doctorate has been in place but has evolved into a slightly different pattern from the European equivalent.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Department of Education now classifies degrees in six categories: associate degrees, bachelor's degrees, first professional degrees, master's degrees, intermediate graduate qualifications and research doctorates.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] The standard academic progression remains bachelor's—master's—(research) doctorate.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] This timetable is only approximate, however, as students in accelerated programs can sometimes earn a bachelor's degree in three years or, on the other hand, a particular dissertation project might take four or more years to complete.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] In addition, a graduate may wait an indeterminate time between degrees before candidacy in the next level or even an additional degree at a level already completed.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Therefore, there is no time limit on the accumulation of academic degrees.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] By far the most common research doctorate is the Doctor of Philosophy (Ph.D.), comprising 98.1% of research doctorates in 2014.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] The Doctor of Education (Ed.D.) made up 1.1% (not including Ed.D.s classified as professional degrees rather than research doctorates) and all other research doctorates were less than 1% in total.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Some schools, mostly junior colleges and community colleges and some four-year schools, offer an associate degree that takes two full years of study.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] These may be in professional or academic fields, and the most common awards are the Associate of Arts (A.A.) and Associate of Science (A.S.) degrees.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Articulation agreements may allow credit earned on an associate degree to be counted toward the completion of a bachelor's degree.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] The "first professional degree" is a graduate-level degree program designed to prepare graduates for professional practice in various fields other than academic scholarship and research.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] First professional degrees require a minimum of two years of college-level education prior to entering the program and a minimum of six years of total college-level education (including that undertaken prior to entry) to complete the program.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Most professional degree programs require a prior bachelor's degree for admission and many require seven or eight years of total study.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] M.D., J.D. or D.O. are named as doctorates but should not be confused with research doctorates such as the Ph.D.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] First professional degrees should also not be confused with professional master's degrees such as the M.Arch. and M.B.A., which are classified as master's degrees, or with intermediate graduate qualifications that also bear the title of doctor, such as D.Min. or D.Psy.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Intermediate graduate qualifications lie between the master's level and doctorate.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] They include awards such as the Certificate of Advanced Study, Graduate Diplomas, Professional Engineer status, and Professional Diplomas, as well as specialist degrees such as Education Specialist, Doctor of Ministry, Doctor of Psychology and the Licentiate in Sacred Theology.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] In 21 US jurisdictions, religious institutions can be authorized to grant religious-exempt (rel. exmpt., rel. expt., etc.) degrees without accreditation or government oversight.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Such degrees are used primarily to attain church-related employment.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Traditionally, more men than women attended and earned degrees at the world's universities.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] A milestone was reached in the United States, according to the 2010 census, as women surpassed men in attaining master's degrees, for the first time.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] The U.S. census reports that 10.5 million men have master's degrees or higher, compared with 10.6 million women.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] The first year that women surpassed men in earning bachelor's degrees was 1996.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Students, the media, and the general public have shown much concern over the value of getting a higher degree in the US ever since the Great Recession of 2007.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Media coverage of the rising costs of higher education and increased student debt have also affected the public's perceptions of whether higher degrees are still worthwhile.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Statistics citing that college graduates make around $1 million more in their lifetimes than those who did not attend college and live longer, healthier lives work in favor of those who argue the continued value of higher degrees.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Studies like the 2011 Learning Gains study by Arum and Roksa, on the other hand, reported that only 55% of students had any learning gains during their first two years of college, which favors the argument that investing in higher education may not still be worth it.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] The Australian Qualifications Framework (AQF) covers 10 levels, of which levels 6–10 correspond to academic degrees.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Also included within the higher education system are: diplomas at level 5 (first year of a degree course); advanced diplomas, at level 6 (associate degree level); and graduate certificates and graduate diplomas, both of which are at level 8 (honours degree level).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] In Australia, most degrees are issued ungraded, with bachelor's degrees with honours being the exception.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Doctorates in Australia may be research doctorates (normally titled PhDs), professional doctorates (normally titled to refer to the field of practice, e.g.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Doctor of Engineering) or higher doctorates (also normally titled to refer to the field of practice).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Extended master's degrees are also allowed to have the word 'doctor' in their title if they are in certain fields, but they are not doctoral degrees.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Like Australia, New Zealand has a 10-level qualifications framework (the New Zealand Qualifications Framework – NZQF) and a referencing exercise has found a one-to-one correspondence between the levels of the two frameworks.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] However, the names given to qualifications at different levels are not the same and New Zealand does not have associate degrees, thus only levels 7–10 correspond to academic degrees.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] These are the bachelor's degree (level 7), bachelor honours degree (level 8), master's degree (level 9) and the doctoral degree (level 10).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] In addition to these, the NZQF has certificates across levels 1–6, diplomas at levels 5 and 6, graduate certificates and graduate diplomas at level 7 (bachelor's), and postgraduate certificates and postgraduate diplomas at level 8 (honours).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Another referencing exercise, comparing the NZQF to the 10-level Irish National Framework for Qualifications, found that degrees were comparable but that further work was needed to improve compatibility at the sub-degree levels (1–6).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Non-degree qualifications at levels 7–9 were not included in the study.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] In New Zealand, master's degrees may be awarded with classified honours (1st, 2:1, 2:2, 3rd) or with distinction or merit.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Undergraduate students in Brazilian universities graduate either with a bachelor's degree, a licentiate degree or a technologist degree.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Bachelor degrees in Brazil normally take four or five years of full-time study to complete, with the exception of the human medicine course, which requires six years.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Licentiate degrees normally take four-years, and are for students who want to qualify as school teachers.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] *Licenciatura* courses exist mostly in mathematics, humanities and natural sciences.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] The technologist degree is available in technology-related fields and can be normally obtained in three years.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] These degrees are for entry into industry.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Admission as an undergraduate student to most top public or private universities in Brazil requires that the applicant pass a competitive entrance examination known as the Vestibular.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Contrary to what happens in the United States, candidates must declare their intended university major when they register for the Vestibular.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Although it is theoretically possible to switch majors afterwards (in a process known within the universities as *transferência interna*), that is actually quite rare in Brazil.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Undergraduate curricula tend to be more rigid than in the United States and there is little room to take classes outside one's major.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Individuals who hold either a bachelor's degree, licentiate or technologist are eligible for admission into graduate courses leading to advanced master's or doctor's degrees.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Criteria for admission into master's and doctor's programs vary in Brazil.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Some universities require that candidates take entrance exams; others make admission decisions based solely on undergraduate transcripts, letters of recommendation and possibly oral interviews.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] In most cases, however, especially for the doctorate, the candidate is required to submit a research plan, and one faculty member must agree to serve as supervisor before the candidate can be admitted into the program.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] There are two types of post-graduate programs: *lato sensu* (specialization and MBAs) and *stricto sensu* (professional master's, master's, and doctorate).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Specializations or MBAs are courses that include taking a minimum number of graduate classes (minimum of 360 hours) but with no need to do research nor defend a thesis, only to present final work showing knowledge acquired.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] It is a professional level where theory and practice are focused broadly.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Professional master's or master's degrees usually take one to two years of full-time study.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] The emphasis of the thesis must be in adding some value to knowledge, but not necessarily in being original.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Doctoral degrees normally take four additional years of full-time study to complete.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Requirements for obtaining a doctor's degree include taking additional advanced courses, passing an oral qualifying exam, and submitting a longer doctoral dissertation which must represent a significant original contribution to knowledge in the field to which the dissertation topic is related.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] That contrasts with master's thesis, which, in addition to being usually shorter than doctoral dissertations, are not required to include creation of new knowledge or revision/reinterpretation of older views/theories.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] The doctoral dissertation is examined in a final oral exam before a panel of at least two members (in the state of São Paulo the preferred number is five, while the other regions prefer three members), usually including one or two external examiners from another university or research institute.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] In Colombia, the system of academic degrees is based in the British model, similar to the U.S. model.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] After completing their "bachillerato" (high school), students can take one of three options.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] The first one is called a *profesional* (professional career), which is similar to a bachelor's degree requiring from four to 6 years of study according to the chosen program.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] The other option is called a *técnico* (technician); this degree consists of two and a half years of study and prepares the student for technical or mechanical labors.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Finally, the third option is called a *tecnólogo* (equivalent to associate degree) and consists of three years of study.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] After this, students, now called *profesional* (professionals), *técnicos* (technicians) or *tecnólogos* (associates), can opt for higher degrees.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Formal education after the bachelor's degree leads to the master's degree with the title of *maestro* and doctorate degrees, known as *doctorado* (doctorate).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] The master's degree normally takes two years.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Students also can take a specialization course, *especialización*, equivalent to a graduate certificate degree, after their bachelor's degree.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] These programs, like in the U.S., are very popular, because it requires only one to two years of study.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] In Colombia, similar to the U.S. system, the students may not go directly to the *doctorado* without having the "master" degree first.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] After completing *enseñanza media* (high school), students receive a *Licenciatura de Enseñanza Media* (high school diploma), which is a requirement for higher education.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Higher-education programs that provide a professional title but not an academic degree are referred to as *carreras técnicas*, which are similar in duration and scope to associate degree programs.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] These are often granted by educational institutions of the type *instituto profesional* (IP) or *centro de formación técnica* (CFT).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Academic degrees in Venezuela start with the *Certificado de Educación Básica* (Certificate of Basic Education), awarded upon completing the 9th grade.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] The next degree is earned upon completing the 11th grade and confers the title of *Bachiller en Ciencias* (High School Graduate of Science), *Bachiller en Humanidades* (High School Graduate of Humanities) or *Técnico en Ciencias* (Science Technician).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Titles at the higher-education level usually depend on the institution handing them out.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Technical schools award the student with the title of *Técnico Superior Universitario* (university higher technician, to distinguish from science technician).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Universities award the student with the title of *ingeniero* (engineer) or with the title *licenciado* (licentiate) after completing a five-year program.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] The ingeniero degree requires more physics than the licenciado degree, but both take five years.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Some higher-education institutions may award *diplomados* (diploma), but the time necessary to obtain one varies.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Medical doctors are awarded the title "Médico Cirujano" after completing a 6-year course of study.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] Postgraduate education in Venezuela follows the conventions of the United States (being named "master's" and "doctorate" after the programs there).
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] The nature of academic degrees from ecclesiastical institutions of education is outlined in the apostolic constitution *Sapientia Christiana*.
[src:certification/academic-degree-p04] The core of degrees granted by pontifical universities consists of three levels: the first is the baccalaureate; the second is the licentiate; the third is the doctorate.
[src:certification/accreditation] Accreditation bodies are established in many economies with the primary purpose of ensuring that conformity assessment bodies are subject to oversight by an authoritative body.
[src:certification/accreditation] Accreditation bodies that have been peer-evaluated as competent sign regional and international arrangements to demonstrate their competence.
[src:certification/accreditation] These accreditation bodies then assess and accredit conformity assessment bodies to the relevant standards.
[src:certification/accreditation] An authoritative body that performs accreditation is called an 'accreditation body'.
[src:certification/accreditation] The International Accreditation Forum (IAF) and International Laboratory Accreditation Cooperation (ILAC) provide international recognitions to accreditation bodies.
[src:certification/accreditation] There are many internationally recognized accreditation bodies approved by the IAF and ILAC.
[src:certification/accreditation] In East Asia, the China National Accreditation Board is the largest, while the United Kingdom Accreditation Service (UKAS) is the largest in Europe.
[src:certification/accreditation] The National Association of Testing Authorities (NATA) and the Joint Accreditation System of Australia and New Zealand (JAS-ANZ) being the largest in the Oceania region, with the South African National Accreditation System being the largest in Africa.
[src:certification/accreditation] For most of the accreditation schemes, international standards issued by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) are used.
[src:certification/accreditation] Many accreditation bodies, such as the UKAS, EIAC, EGAC, PNAC, IAS, NABCB operate according to processes developed by the ISO as specified in ISO/IEC 17011.
[src:certification/american-society-for-quality] The **American Society for Quality** (**ASQ**), formerly the **American Society for Quality Control** (**ASQC**), is a society of quality professionals, with more than 30,000 members, in more than 140 countries.
[src:certification/american-society-for-quality] ASQC was established on 16 February 1946 by 253 members in Milwaukee, Wisconsin, with George D.
[src:certification/american-society-for-quality] The organization was first created as a way for quality experts and manufacturers to sustain quality-improvement techniques used during World War II.
[src:certification/american-society-for-quality] In 1948, ASQC's Code of Ethics established standards for members to conduct their activities and business.
[src:certification/american-society-for-quality] Feigenbaum served as president of the society in 1961–63.
[src:certification/american-society-for-quality] In 1997, the members of the organization voted to change its name from "American Society for Quality Control" to "American Society for Quality".
[src:certification/american-society-for-quality] ASQ provides its members with certification, training, publications, conferences, and other services.
[src:certification/american-society-for-quality] ASQ is a founding partner of the American Customer Satisfaction Index (ACSI), a quarterly economic indicator.
[src:certification/american-society-for-quality] Since 1989, ASQ has administered the annual Malcolm Baldrige National Quality Award.
[src:certification/american-society-for-quality] The ASQ also gives the Dorian Shainin Medal, which is awarded annually for the "Development and Application of Creative or Unique Statistical Approaches in the Solving of Problems Relative to the Quality of Product or Service".
[src:certification/american-society-for-quality] ASQ offers 18 professional certifications relating to various aspects of the quality profession.
[src:certification/american-society-for-quality] Professional certification exams are translated into five languages included English, Korean, Mandarin, Portuguese, and Spanish.
[src:certification/american-society-for-quality] Exams are given nationally and, to a limited degree, worldwide several times annually.
[src:certification/american-society-for-quality] The body of knowledge for each certification is maintained through peer review every few years on a rotating schedule.
[src:certification/american-society-for-quality] In 1968, the first ASQ certification was offered.
[src:certification/american-society-for-quality] In 2016, ASQ's certification exam delivery method changed from paper to computer-based testing at Prometric nationwide testing facilities.
[src:certification/atikamekw] The **Atikamekw** are an Indigenous people in Canada.
[src:certification/atikamekw] Their historic territory, *Nitaskinan* ('Our Land'), is in the upper Saint-Maurice River valley of Quebec (about 300 kilometres (190 mi) north of Montreal).
[src:certification/atikamekw] One of the main communities is Manawan, about 160 kilometres (99 mi) northeast of Montreal.
[src:certification/atikamekw] Their current population is around 8,000.
[src:certification/atikamekw] They have a tradition of agriculture as well as fishing, hunting, and gathering.
[src:certification/atikamekw] They maintain close ties with the Innu people, who were their historical allies against the Inuit.
[src:certification/atikamekw] The Atikamekw language, likely a variety of Cree in the Algonquian family, is closely related to that of the Innu.
[src:certification/atikamekw] It is still in everyday use, being among the Indigenous languages least threatened with extinction.
[src:certification/atikamekw] Their traditional ways of life are endangered, however, as their homeland has largely been taken over by logging companies.
[src:certification/atikamekw] Their name, which literally means 'lake whitefish', is sometimes also spelt *Atihkamekw*, *Attikamekw*, *Attikamek*, or *Atikamek*.
[src:certification/atikamekw] The French colonists referred to them as *Têtes-de-Boules*, meaning 'Ball-Heads' or 'Round-Heads'.
[src:certification/atikamekw] Some Atihkamekw families make their living making traditional birchbark baskets and canoes.
[src:certification/atikamekw] Early French historical documents begin to mention the Atikamekw at beginning of the 17th century, when they lived in the boreal forest of the upper Mauricie.
[src:certification/atikamekw] In these early documents, the French colonists recorded the Atikamekw as *"Atikamegouékhi"*, an effort to transliterate their name for themselves.
[src:certification/atikamekw] The Atikamekw were described as a group of 500 to 600 people, who made up "one of the nations more considerable of the north".
[src:certification/atikamekw] For food, they fished, hunted, and trapped.
[src:certification/atikamekw] They supplemented their diet with agricultural products made and processed by women, such as corn and maple syrup.
[src:certification/atikamekw] The latter was boiled to reduce as a syrup after sap was tapped from maple trees.
[src:certification/atikamekw] Both men and women made tools from wood and animal parts, such as bone and tendon.
[src:certification/atikamekw] The women made clothing from tanned animal hides.
[src:certification/atikamekw] Tribal members traded with other native peoples in nearby areas, but trading networks connected along long distances.
[src:certification/atikamekw] In summer, the Atikamekw would gather at places like Wemotaci.
[src:certification/atikamekw] In the fall, they would pack for the winter season and disperse into smaller encampments through the boreal forest.
[src:certification/atikamekw] After the French entered the trading network, they introduced new, European manufactured goods, such as metal tools.
[src:certification/atikamekw] The Atikamekw traded furs for such goods, becoming increasingly dependent on European goods in the fur trade.
[src:certification/atikamekw] They were described as a peaceful people, sharing the region with the Innu (Montagnais) in the east, the Cree in the north, and Algonquin to the south.
[src:certification/atikamekw] The Mohawk of the Iroquois Confederacy, whose five nations were based south of the Great Lakes, competed with them for the lucrative beaver trade and over hunting grounds.
[src:certification/atikamekw] Through their Innu allies, the Atikamekw caught new infectious diseases that were endemic among the Europeans.
[src:certification/atikamekw] Around 1670-1680, a smallpox epidemic devastated the Atikamekw tribe.
[src:certification/atikamekw] The French pulled the Atikamekw into a trade war between the Montagnais (Innu) and the Mohawk, in which the Atikamekw and Innu did not fare well.
[src:certification/atikamekw] Many of the Atikamekw who had survived the smallpox were killed by the more powerful Mohawk.
[src:certification/atikamekw] However, at the start of the 18th century, a group called *"Tête-de-Boule"* by the French reappeared in the region.
[src:certification/atikamekw] While there exists no certainty as to the origin of this group, they may have been a regrouping of the few Atikamekw survivors and who were possibly associated with other indigenous nomadic tribes.
[src:certification/atikamekw] But they are considered to be unrelated to the former Atikamekw even though they lived in the same area and took on the same name.
[src:certification/atikamekw] The Atikamekw have their own traditional culture, language and rituals, though they had strong influences from the neighboring peoples.
[src:certification/atikamekw] From this grouping, three prominent communities developed.
[src:certification/atikamekw] Each spoke the same language but with unique dialects.
[src:certification/atikamekw] Members of the tribe as a whole generally speak the Atikamekw language, but the majority do not write it.
[src:certification/atikamekw] Traditionally, the Atikamekw lived in dome-shaped homes, which they created with branches and covered with bark called *"piskokan"*.
[src:certification/atikamekw] They covered the floor with spruce boughs, and used furs for beds and blankets.
[src:certification/atikamekw] The Atikamekw preserved meat by smoking and drying it, a process still practiced by some families.
[src:certification/atikamekw] Women collected berries and processed them into a paste that could be preserved for several weeks.
[src:certification/atikamekw] They chew the sap of Abies balsamea as a cold remedy, and use the boughs as mats for the tent floor.
[src:certification/atikamekw] The making of hunting equipment (bows, snowshoes, sled dog) as well as clothing and blankets, was in former times a task necessary for survival.
[src:certification/atikamekw] The Atikamekw developed a distinctive way to decorate their clothing.
[src:certification/atikamekw] They covered ceremonial robes with bells made of bones emptied of the marrow.
[src:certification/atikamekw] The Atikamekw have been recognized for their skill in crafting birch bark items such as baskets and canoes, decorating the pieces with beautiful designs.
[src:certification/atikamekw] These skills have been transmitted from generation to generation.
[src:certification/atikamekw] The Atikamekw are known as the "people of the bark" for their craft.
[src:certification/atikamekw] The people of Obedjiwan make birch bark handicrafts less frequently than do other communities, since their environment in the boreal forest is dominated by conifer trees.
[src:certification/atikamekw] The Atikamekw recognize six seasons in the year, each of which has a principal activity.
[src:certification/atikamekw] The seasons begin with *Sîkon*, in late winter.
[src:certification/atikamekw] The Atikamekw use this time to make bark baskets, which they can use to hold the maple-sap gathered in this time of year.
[src:certification/atikamekw] After *Sîkon* is *Mirôskamin*, what European-Canadians would call Spring.
[src:certification/atikamekw] In this season, the Atikamekw generally fished and hunted for partridge.
[src:certification/atikamekw] These activities continue through *Nîpin* (Summer).
[src:certification/atikamekw] During *Takwâkin* (autumn), the Atikamekw would go hunting for moose.
[src:certification/atikamekw] A successful hunt required the careful removal of the skin of the moose, making offerings, and processing the meat for preservation through smoking and drying, for moose "jerky".
[src:certification/atikamekw] Women worked to make the hides usable: remove the hairs from the moose hide; soak, deflesh and tan the hide; and cut it into thin, flexible strips to weave netting for snowshoes.
[src:certification/atikamekw] During the onset of winter, or *Pîtcipipôn*, the men would trap for beaver.
[src:certification/atikamekw] During the winter, or *Pipôn*, the men would make nets to fish under the ice, while others produce snowshoes.
[src:certification/atikamekw] In conjunction with the seasons, the Atikamekw divide the year into 12 months.
[src:certification/atikamekw] The month names are based on the primary activity or observation of nature in that period.
[src:certification/atikamekw] Filmmaker Chloé Leriche has made two films about the Atikamekw peoples, *Before the Streets (Avant les rues)* in 2016 and *Atikamekw Suns (Soleils Atikamekw)* in 2023.
[src:certification/audit] Auditors consider the propositions before them, obtain evidence, document their findings, and evaluate the propositions in their auditing report.
[src:certification/audit] Audits provide third-party assurance to various stakeholders that the subject matter is free from material misstatement.
[src:certification/audit] The term is most frequently applied to audits of the financial information relating to a legal person.
[src:certification/audit] Other commonly audited areas include: secretarial and compliance, internal controls, quality management, project management, water management, and energy conservation.
[src:certification/audit] As a result of an audit, stakeholders may evaluate and improve the effectiveness of risk management, control, and governance over the subject matter.
[src:certification/audit] In recent years auditing has expanded to encompass many areas of public and corporate life.
[src:certification/audit] Professor Michael Power refers to this extension of auditing practices as the "Audit Society".
[src:certification/audit] The word "audit" derives from the Latin word *audire* which means "to hear".
[src:certification/audit] Auditing has been a safeguard measure since ancient times.
[src:certification/audit] During medieval times, when manual bookkeeping was prevalent, auditors in Britain used to hear the accounts read out for them and checked that the organization's personnel were not negligent or fraudulent.
[src:certification/audit] In 1951, Moyer identified that the most important duty of the auditor was to detect fraud.
[src:certification/audit] Chatfield documented that early United States auditing was viewed mainly as verification of bookkeeping detail.
[src:certification/audit] The Central Auditing Commission of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union (Russian: Центральная ревизионная комиссия КПСС) operated from 1921 to 1990.
[src:certification/audit] An **information technology audit**, or **information systems audit**, is an examination of the management controls within an Information technology (IT) infrastructure.
[src:certification/audit] The evaluation of obtained evidence determines if the information systems are safeguarding assets, maintaining data integrity, and operating effectively to achieve the organization's goals or objectives.
[src:certification/audit] These reviews may be performed in conjunction with a financial statement audit, internal audit, or other form of attestation engagement.
[src:certification/audit] Due to strong incentives (including taxation, misselling and other forms of fraud) to misstate financial information, auditing has become a legal requirement for many entities who have the power to exploit financial information for personal gain.
[src:certification/audit] Traditionally, audits were mainly associated with gaining information about financial systems and the financial records of a company or a business.
[src:certification/audit] Financial audits also assess whether a business or corporation adheres to legal duties as well as other applicable statutory customs and regulations.
[src:certification/audit] Financial audits are performed to ascertain the validity and reliability of information, as well as to provide an assessment of a system's internal control.
[src:certification/audit] The third party auditor will express an opinion of the person, organization, or system in question.
[src:certification/audit] The opinion given on financial statements will depend on the audit evidence obtained.
[src:certification/audit] A statutory audit is a legally required review of the accuracy of a company's or government's financial statements and records.
[src:certification/audit] The purpose of a statutory audit is to determine whether an organization provides a fair and accurate representation of its financial position by examining information such as bank balances, bookkeeping records, and financial transactions.
[src:certification/audit] Due to constraints, an audit seeks to provide only **reasonable assurance** that the statements are free from material error.
[src:certification/audit] Hence, statistical sampling is often adopted in audits.
[src:certification/audit] In the case of financial audits, a set of financial statements are said to be true and fair when they are free of material misstatements – a concept influenced by both quantitative (numerical) and qualitative factors.
[src:certification/audit] Recently, the argument that auditing should go beyond just true and fair is gaining momentum, and the US Public Company Accounting Oversight Board has come out with a concept release on the same.
[src:certification/audit] Cost accounting is a process for verifying the cost of manufacturing or producing of any article, on the basis of accounts measuring the use of material, labor or other items of cost.
[src:certification/audit] The term "cost audit" refers to a systematic and accurate verification of the cost accounts and records, and checking for adherence to the cost accounting objectives.
[src:certification/audit] In most nations, an audit must adhere to generally accepted standards established by governing bodies.
[src:certification/audit] These standards assure third parties or external users that they can rely upon the auditor's opinion on the fairness of financial statements or other subjects on which the auditor expresses an opinion.
[src:certification/audit] The audit must therefore be precise and accurate, containing no additional misstatements or errors.
[src:certification/audit] In the US, audits of publicly traded companies are governed by rules laid down by the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (PCAOB), which was established by Section 404 of the Sarbanes–Oxley Act of 2002.
[src:certification/audit] Such an audit is called an integrated audit, where auditors, in addition to an opinion on the financial statements, must also express an opinion on the *effectiveness* of a company's *internal control* over financial reporting, in accordance with PCAOB Auditing Standard No.
[src:certification/audit] There are also new types of integrated auditing becoming available that use unified compliance material (see the unified compliance section in Regulatory compliance).
[src:certification/audit] Due to the increasing number of regulations and need for operational transparency, organizations are adopting risk-based audits that can cover multiple regulations and standards from a single audit event.
[src:certification/audit] This is a very new approach in some sectors to ensure that all the necessary governance requirements can be met without duplicating effort from both audit and audit hosting resources.
[src:certification/audit] The purpose of an assessment is to measure something or calculate a value for it.
[src:certification/audit] An auditor's objective is to determine whether financial statements are presented fairly, in all material respects, and are free of material misstatement.
[src:certification/audit] Although the process of producing an assessment may involve an audit by an independent professional, its purpose is to provide a measurement rather than to express an opinion about the fairness of statements or quality of performance.
[src:certification/audit] The most commonly used external audit standards are the US GAAS of the American Institute of Certified Public Accountants and the International Standards on Auditing (ISA) developed by the International Auditing and Assurance Standard.
[src:certification/audit] Recent advances in artificial intelligence and automation are reshaping audit practice.
[src:certification/audit] Audit firms now apply data analytics and machine-learning techniques to analyze entire datasets instead of statistical samples, improving anomaly detection and efficiency.
[src:certification/audit] However, these technologies also introduce challenges related to data quality, algorithmic bias, and the need for professional judgment.
[src:certification/audit] A performance audit is an independent examination of a program, function, operation or the management systems and procedures of a governmental or non-profit entity to assess whether the entity is achieving economy, efficiency and effectiveness in the employment of available resources.
[src:certification/audit] Safety, security, information systems performance, and environmental concerns are increasingly the subject of audits.
[src:certification/audit] There are now audit professionals who specialize in security audits and information systems audits.
[src:certification/audit] With nonprofit organizations and government agencies, there has been an increasing need for performance audits, examining their success in satisfying mission objectives.
[src:certification/audit] Quality audits are performed to verify conformance to standards through reviewing objective evidence.
[src:certification/audit] A system of quality audits may verify the effectiveness of a quality management system.
[src:certification/audit] This is part of certifications such as ISO 9001.
[src:certification/audit] Quality audits are essential to verify the existence of objective evidence showing conformance to required processes, to assess how successfully processes have been implemented, and to judge the effectiveness of achieving any defined target levels.
[src:certification/audit] Quality audits are also necessary to provide evidence concerning reduction and elimination of problem areas, and they are a hands-on management tool for achieving continual improvement in an organization.
[src:certification/audit] To benefit the organization, quality auditing should not only report non-conformance and corrective actions but also highlight areas of good practice and provide evidence of conformance.
[src:certification/audit] In this way, other departments may share information and amend their working practices as a result, also enhancing continual improvement.
[src:certification/audit] A project audit provides an opportunity to uncover issues, concerns and challenges encountered during the project lifecycle.
[src:certification/audit] Conducted midway through the project, a project audit provides the project manager, project sponsor and project team an interim view of what has gone well, as well as what needs to be improved to successfully complete the project.
[src:certification/audit] If done at the close of a project, the audit can be used to develop success criteria for future projects by providing a forensic review.
[src:certification/audit] This review identifies which elements of the project were successfully managed and which ones presented challenges.
[src:certification/audit] As a result, the review will help the organization identify what it needs to do to avoid repeating the same mistakes on future projects.
[src:certification/audit] An energy audit is an inspection, survey and analysis of energy flows for energy conservation in a building, process or system to reduce the amount of energy input into the system without negatively affecting the output.
[src:certification/audit] An operations audit is an examination of the operations of the client's business.
[src:certification/audit] In this audit, the auditor thoroughly examines the efficiency, effectiveness and economy of the operations with which the management of the client is achieving its objectives.
[src:certification/audit] The operational audit goes beyond internal controls issues since management does not achieve its objectives merely by compliance to a satisfactory system of internal controls.
[src:certification/audit] Operational audits cover any matters which may be commercially unsound.
[src:certification/audit] The objective of operational audit is to examine three E's, namely: Effectiveness – doing the right things with the least wastage of resources, Efficiency – performing work in the least possible time, and Economy – balance between benefits and costs to run the operation.
[src:certification/audit] A control self-assessment is a commonly used tool for completing an operations audit.
[src:certification/audit] Also referred to as forensic accountancy, forensic accountant or forensic accounting, a forensic audit is an investigative audit in which accountants specialized in both accounting and investigation seek to uncover frauds, missing money and negligence.
[src:certification/cem-kaner] He has also worked as a user interface designer.
[src:certification/cem-kaner] In 2004 he cofounded the non-profit Association for Software Testing.
[src:certification/cem-kaner] Kaner received a Bachelor's Degree from Brock University in 1974, having focused on mathematics and philosophy.
[src:certification/cem-kaner] He went on to receive a Ph.D. in experimental psychology from McMaster University in 1984, with a dissertation in the area of psychophysics (the measurement of perceptual experiences).
[src:certification/cem-kaner] He later attended Golden Gate University Law School, with a primary interest in the law of software quality, graduating with a J.D. in 1994.
[src:certification/cem-kaner] Kaner worked as a part-time volunteer for the Santa Clara, California Department of Consumer Affairs, investigating and mediating consumer complaints.
[src:certification/cem-kaner] In the 1990s, he got trial experience working as a full-time volunteer Deputy District Attorney, and later counselled independent consultants, technical book writers, and independent test labs on contract and intellectual property issues as an attorney.
[src:certification/cem-kaner] In 1999, he was elected to the American Law Institute, after being in practice for only five years.
[src:certification/cem-kaner] This experience led him, in collaboration with David Pels, to publish *Bad Software: What To Do When Software Fails* in 1997.
[src:certification/certification] As a rule, certificates must be renewed and periodically reviewed by a certifying regulatory body responsible for the validity of the certificate's assessment methods.
[src:certification/certification] The certifying body can be either a state authority or an independent private company.
[src:certification/certification] Certificates may even be issued by the companies themselves that use them, primarily as a marketing gimmick, which can be characterized as "cheap talk," meaning a trick that does not guarantee trust.
[src:certification/certification] A study conducted by the Certification Board of Computing Professionals (CBCP) showed that the average salary increase for IT professionals who obtained CompTIA certificates was 15%.
[src:certification/certification] Similarly, a study by the Project Management Institute (PMI) found that certified PMP® project managers earn on average 20% more than their non-certified counterparts.
[src:certification/certification] One of the most common types of certification in modern society is professional certification, where a person is certified as being able to competently complete a job or task, usually by the passing of an examination and/or the completion of a program of study.
[src:certification/certification] Some professional certifications also require that one obtain work experience in a related field before the certification can be awarded.
[src:certification/certification] Some professional certifications are valid for a lifetime upon completing all certification requirements.
[src:certification/certification] Others expire after a certain period of time and have to be maintained with further education and/or testing.
[src:certification/certification] Certifications can differ within a profession by the level or specific area of expertise to which they refer.
[src:certification/certification] For example, in the IT Industry there are different certifications available for software tester, project manager, and developer.
[src:certification/certification] Also, the Joint Commission on Allied Health Personnel in Ophthalmology offers three certifications in the same profession, but with increasing complexity.
[src:certification/certification] Certification does not designate that a person has sufficient knowledge in a subject area, only that they passed the test.
[src:certification/certification] This of course apples only to exam-based certifications.
[src:certification/certification] Education-based certifications, require that a person completes a course of study that satisfies certain body of knowledge claims to demonstrate that the person has sufficient knowledge in the subject area.
[src:certification/certification] Certification does not refer to the state of legally being able to practice or work in a profession.
[src:certification/certification] Usually, licensure is administered by a governmental entity for public protection purposes and a professional association administers certification.
[src:certification/certification] Licensure and certification are similar in that they both require the demonstration of a certain level of knowledge or ability.
[src:certification/certification] Another common type of certification in modern society is product certification.
[src:certification/certification] This refers to processes intended to determine if a product meets minimum standards, similar to quality assurance.
[src:certification/certification] Different certification systems exist in each country.
[src:certification/certification] For example, in Russia it is the GOST R Rostest.
[src:certification/certification] Certification is dependent on meeting specific requirements that are defined in a technical standard.
[src:certification/certification] This is either an international standard or a private standard.
[src:certification/certification] ISEAL Alliance and Global Food Safety Initiative are examples of private organizations who represent the private sector.
[src:certification/certification] Promoting certification in supply chains of private corporations by recognizing scheme owners who adopt private standards.
[src:certification/certification] In comparison, the public sector and Intergovernmental organizations (IGOs) recommend international standards.
[src:certification/certification] Scheme owners using private standards require scheme fees, which is typically an annual payment for issuing a certificate.
[src:certification/certification] Whereas international standards do not allow scheme ownership and do not require fees to issue a certificate.
[src:certification/certification] Further differences between international standards and private standards are explained in a paper from ISO.
[src:certification/certification] In the European Union, a notified Body is an organization accredited by an accreditation body for the purpose of providing third-party certification and testing services of the standards and regulations within the purview of the accreditation body.
[src:certification/certification] This serves to enforce regulatory compliance with these codes, and gives providers of goods and services a means of demonstrating compliance by way of an official certification mark or a declaration of conformity.
[src:certification/certification] For software testing, the certifications can be grouped into exam-based and education-based.
[src:certification/certification] For exam-based certifications the candidate must pass an exam, which can also be learned by self-study.
[src:certification/certification] For example, for International Software Testing Qualifications Board Certified Tester by the International Software Testing Qualifications Board or Certified Software Tester by QAI or Certified Software Quality Engineer by American Society for Quality.
[src:certification/certification] Education-based certifications are the instructor-led sessions, where each course has to be passed.
[src:certification/certification] The Certified Software Test Professional (CSTP), the Certified Agile Software Test Professional (CASTP), the Certified Test Manager (CTM) and other certifications by Institute for Software Testing are such examples.
[src:certification/certification] It is common for people who require certifications to undergo paid structured learning to help them achieve their goals.
[src:certification/certification] In certification systems based on participation, certification is developed by a network of participants, such as groups of producers and consumers.
[src:certification/certification] These systems are based on trust and networks for sharing knowledge and experience.
[src:certification/certification] In such cases, we refer to them as participatory guarantee systems.
